This patch series adds client-initiated multipath support to the NFSv4.1
client. The feature allows a single mount to use multiple server addresses
by distributing NFS operations across separate TCP connections.

Motivation
==========

Enterprise NFS deployments commonly have multiple network paths between
clients and storage arrays (multiple NICs, multiple fabric switches).
Without multipath, one path sits idle while the other carries all traffic.
Administrators resort to multiple mounts, LACP bonding, or vendor-specific
solutions.

This implementation is client-only -- no server changes are required.
It works with any standard NFSv4.1 server (Linux nfsd, NetApp ONTAP,
Huawei OceanStor, VAST Data, etc.).

Design
======

The implementation adds a new mount option "remoteaddrs=" that accepts
a tilde-separated list of IPv4 or IPv6 addresses:

  mount -t nfs4 -o vers=4.1,remoteaddrs=10.0.0.1~10.0.0.2  \
      10.0.0.1:/export /mnt

After the NFSv4.1 session is established with the primary server,
additional TCP connections are created to each address in the list
and added to the SunRPC transport switch (xprt_switch). The stock
round-robin dispatch distributes operations across all transports.

The NFSv4.1 session model provides ordered execution (slot table),
deterministic duplicate detection (per-slot cache), and transparent
failover across all transports with zero additional code.

Patches
=======

  1/6  fs/nfs/Kconfig + Makefile: add CONFIG_DNFS option
  2/6  fs/nfs/internal.h: add dnfs fields to mount structures
  3/6  fs/nfs/fs_context.c: parse remoteaddrs= mount option
  4/6  fs/nfs/client.c: propagate dnfs option through nfs_client
  5/6  fs/nfs/super.c: transfer dnfs state during mount/unmount
  6/6  fs/nfs/nfs4client.c: create extra transports after session

Testing
=======

- Unit tests for option parsing (user-mode compilation with mocks)
- Integration tests with Linux nfsd on VM
- Verified against Huawei OceanStor Pacific 9550
- /etc/fstab compatibility verified
- IPv4 and IPv6 address formats tested
- Error injection: invalid addresses, network failures, timeouts

